{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17492589","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17492589"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T06:36:52+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T06:36:52+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1107"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1107","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1107"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.55,0.05,0.31,0.01,0.08]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1107"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"92063"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1107","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1107"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1107"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"75479"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"36"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"214"},{"type":"tags","id":"1149"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2838"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31436"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"92063","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/92063"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 74-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-month history of a painless swelling in the left side of his scrotum. He has a medical history of chronic obstructive pulmonary disease with two hospital admissions for infective exacerbations in the past five years, and hypertension. His medications include salbutamol inhaler and amlodipine. He does not report any trauma to the area, weight loss, night sweats, abdominal pain, or any other concerns.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There are scattered wheezes in the lung bases. The scrotal swelling is non-tender and the spermatic cord can be felt as a distinct structure above it. The swelling transilluminates brightly (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely cause of the swelling?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Idiopathic","Filariasis","Patent processus vaginalis","Trauma","Infection"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with classic features of a hydrocele - a painless scrotal swelling that transilluminates and is separate from the spermatic cord. In adults in Australia, \u003Cstrong\u003Eidiopathic\u003C/strong\u003E causes account for the majority of hydroceles, with fluid accumulating in the tunica vaginalis due to an imbalance between secretion and absorption.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFilariasis\u003C/strong\u003E due to \u003Cem\u003EWuchereria bancrofti\u003C/em\u003E is the most common cause of hydrocele worldwide, particularly in endemic regions of Asia, Africa, and South America. However, this is extremely rare in Australia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Epatent processus vaginalis\u003C/strong\u003E is the most common cause of hydrocele in infants and young children, where the connection between the peritoneal cavity and scrotum fails to close during development. This would be highly unusual in a 74-year-old man.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETrauma\u003C/strong\u003E can cause a hydrocele, but there is no history of injury in this case, and traumatic hydroceles are typically accompanied by pain and other signs of injury.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInfection\u003C/strong\u003E such as epididymitis can lead to a reactive hydrocele, but this would typically present acutely with pain, erythema, and systemic symptoms, none of which are present in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe key examination findings that help confirm the diagnosis include positive transillumination (indicating fluid-filled sac) and the ability to palpate the spermatic cord separately from the swelling (distinguishing it from other conditions like inguinal hernias).\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["In adult males, most hydroceles are idiopathic and painless with no clear underlying cause found.","Transillumination is a key examination finding that helps distinguish hydroceles from other scrotal masses.","The ability to palpate the spermatic cord separately from the swelling is an important diagnostic feature of hydrocele."],"references":["Dagur G, Gandhi J, Suh Y, Weissbart S, Sheynkin YR, Smith NL, Joshi G, Khan SA. Classifying Hydroceles of the Pelvis and Groin: An Overview of Etiology, Secondary Complications, Evaluation, and Management. Curr Urol. 2017 Apr;10(1):1-14. doi: 10.1159/000447145. Epub 2017 Mar 30. PMID: 28559772; PMCID: PMC5436019."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"75479"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1107"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"18364"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"18364","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/18364"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/dda6db62-511f-4dd7-9047-66e9587fb949.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/dda6db62-511f-4dd7-9047-66e9587fb949.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":493,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"75479","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/75479"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-16T17:54:43+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-16T17:54:44+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1107"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"92063"}